One more idea came out of this.

Medusa shouldn’t only store serpents.

She should shed them.

Just as real snakes shed their skin, Pantheon could periodically ask:

“Can this doctrine be rewritten at a higher SCR without losing its invariants?”

If yes, the old version becomes provenance, and a new, smaller, denser serpent replaces it.

That gives Medusa a genuine life cycle:

* Capture — discover a new pattern.
* Grow — connect it to other serpents.
* Coil — compress it into a stable invariant.
* Shed — rewrite it at a higher SCR while preserving identity.
* Spawn — when the invariant proves generative, branch it into new serpents.

That’s a surprisingly elegant fit with the mythology: Medusa’s “hair” becomes a living, evolving ecology of algorithmic invariants rather than a static collection. And because each serpent is compressible and rehydratable, the whole head becomes a compact, resilient memory system rather than just an archive.